# Minerva

Minerva is a legacy augmented-reality engine built around MSL (Minerva
Specification Language). An MSL application describes scene objects,
rendering, tracking, physics, sensors, controllers, actuators, sounds, and
Python-backed game logic.

The repository currently builds the complete engine and its original
frontends:

- `minerva` preprocesses and parses an MSL source file, creates the legacy
  `data.dat` application package, and prepares a player executable.
- `player` loads a packaged application and runs its camera, tracking,
  physics, input, logic, audio, and rendering loop.
- `minerva_smoke` checks core initialization or prints preprocessed MSL.
- `minerva_kernel_tests` contains the automated engine test suite.

## Current platform support

The maintained and tested configurations are Windows x64 using either:

- Visual Studio 2026 with vcpkg static dependencies; or
- MSYS2 UCRT64 with matching MSYS2 packages.

The engine uses C++17 and CMake 3.20 or newer. Other platforms and toolchains
may work, but they are not currently verified by this repository.

## Quick start

Install the dependencies described in [BUILDING.md](BUILDING.md), then choose
one of the supplied presets.

Visual Studio:

```powershell
cmake --preset visual-studio-debug
cmake --build --preset visual-studio-debug
ctest --preset visual-studio-debug
```

MSYS2 UCRT64:

```powershell
cmake --preset windows-msys2-debug
cmake --build --preset windows-msys2-debug
ctest --preset windows-msys2-debug
```

The complete setup, Release presets, target list, troubleshooting guidance,
and parser-regeneration instructions are in [BUILDING.md](BUILDING.md).

## Running the tools

Run the core smoke check:

```powershell
.\build\windows-msys2-debug\minerva_smoke.exe
```

Print the preprocessed form of an MSL file without running the full engine:

```powershell
.\build\windows-msys2-debug\minerva_smoke.exe path\to\application.mrv
```

Build a legacy application package:

```powershell
.\build\windows-msys2-debug\minerva.exe path\to\application.mrv
```

Run a packaged application:

```powershell
.\build\windows-msys2-debug\player.exe
```

Visual Studio binaries are under
`build\visual-studio-debug\Debug` instead. The player expects `data.dat` in
its application directory and requires suitable camera, graphics, audio, and
tracking resources.

## Engine capabilities

Minerva includes:

- 2D images and TrueType text;
- 3D OBJ, OreJ, and 3DS models;
- OpenGL rendering and Bullet physics;
- SDL input, image, text, and audio integration;
- ARToolKit marker tracking over OpenCV camera frames;
- sensor/controller/actuator game logic;
- embedded Python scripting through the MGE module; and
- MSL preprocessing, parsing, resource collection, and ZIP packaging.

## Known limitations

- There is no CMake install or deployment target yet. Run from the build tree;
  copying an executable alone does not produce a complete runtime.
- No ready-to-run sample application or camera calibration package is
  currently included.
- `player` requires real camera and graphics/audio hardware and is not launched
  by the automated test suite.
- The legacy authoring frontend has path and executable-discovery limitations,
  particularly with spaces, long paths, and Visual Studio multi-configuration
  output directories.
- Invalid MSL and missing resources can terminate the process instead of
  returning a recoverable diagnostic.
- Visual Studio Debug builds currently warn about the package-provided SDLmain
  runtime and missing SDLmain debug symbols.
- The codebase retains legacy ownership and lifecycle behavior. Treat it as
  experimental when loading untrusted files or embedding it in another
  process.

